         <div xml:id="main">
            <head type="incipit">
               <supplied reason="XTF-compatibility">29/1/70 ¶  ¶ Since last writing to you, dear Mr Bentham, I have examined most of the Austr. Liliaceae, and thereby a good deal of new knowledge is gained. ¶  Endlichers Thysanotus micranthus belongs n...</supplied>
            </head>
            <p rend="number" xml:lang="en">70.01.29a</p>
            <p rend="correspondent" xml:lang="en">To George Bentham</p>
            <p rend="location" xml:lang="en">RBG Kew, Kew correspondence, Australia, Mueller, 1858-70, f. 420.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">29/1/70</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Since last writing to you, dear Mr Bentham, I have examined most of the Austr. <name key="Liliaceae">Liliaceae</name>, and thereby a good deal of new knowledge is gained.<note xml:id="ftn1" type="footnote" n="1">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <seg style="">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
                     </seg>As was his usual practice, M published the results of his analysis (see B70.01.01, pp. 64-80) before Bentham undertook his review for Bentham (1863-78); see Lucas (2003).</p>
               </note> Endlichers <name key="Thysanotus%20micranthus">Thysanotus micranthus</name> belongs not to the genus, but is identical with [my] Caesia (Corynotheca) [d]ichotoma; <name key="Caesia%20corymbosa">Caesia corymbosa</name> &amp; C. spiralis form at least a section, as Dr Hooker indicated, if not a genus, to which the name <name key="Chamaescilla">Chamaescilla</name> might be given. I find over a <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">dozen</hi>
               </seg> ovules in each of the cells occasionally. In working on Anguillaria, I compared the allied Extraaustr. genera, and accept with As. Gray &amp; Torrey<note xml:id="ftn2" type="footnote" n="2">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <seg style="">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>See, for example, A. </seg>Gray (1867), p. 524, <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>and Torrey (1843), vol. 2, p. 316, of each of which M owned copies.</p>
               </note>
               <name key="Melanthium">Melanthium</name> for the Virginian &amp; Sibirian plants, bringing the Cape <name key="Melanthium">Melanthium</name>s to Anguillaria, from which they only differ in deciduous sepals, A. australis namely (only 1 sp. in all Austr) having a persistent calyx, contrary to RBr's definition. <name key="Iphigenia">Iphigenia</name> is more closely allied to <name key="Ornithoglossum">Ornithoglossum</name> in the presense of pedicels, bracteoles &amp; other respects. Androcymbium has at least in A eucomoides a persisitent calyx, altho' Kunth says it is deciduous.<note xml:id="ftn3" type="footnote" n="3">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <seg style="">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
                     </seg>Kunth (1833-50), vol. 4, p. 152. </p>
               </note>
               <name key="Iphigenia">Iphigenia</name> has the normal extrorse anthers, altho' Kunth founded his genus chiefly on the supposed introrse anthers; and so I had endless errors &amp; misunderstandings to clear up. This all will render your own final researches far less labourious. RBr's &amp; Miquels <name key="Smilax">Smilax</name> species are reducible to 2, but I have a new third one. The aestivation is very important in all genera.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>A sad mishap has befallen a portion of the <name key="Euphorbiaceae">Euphorbiaceae</name>. Prof Baillon had since a good while a great supplemental lot, which was to have gone to you after examination. Before however my order to this effect reached Mons. Ramel of Paris,<note xml:id="ftn4" type="footnote" n="4">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <seg style="">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
                     </seg>Letter not found.</p>
               </note> the latter had shipped the whole in the Royal Standard, which steamer was totally <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">lost</hi>
               </seg> at the Brazilian Coast.<note xml:id="ftn5" type="footnote" n="5">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <seg style="">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
                     </seg>Accounts of the wreck of the <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Royal standard</seg> appear in the <seg style="font-style: italic; ">London Times</seg> in the week beginning 15 November 1869.</p>
               </note> I hope Prof Baillon <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">did</hi>
               </seg> work out all the species before he returned them. My genus <name key="Dissiliaria">Dissiliaria</name> is described from this lot in the Adansonia,<note xml:id="ftn6" type="footnote" n="6">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <seg style="">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
                     </seg>Baillon (1867), p. 356-60. Baillon cited M's herbarium, thus the specimen upon which the genus was founded was lost in the wreck.</p>
               </note> also the <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">bisexual flower of <name key="Coelebogyne">Coelebogyne</name>
                  </hi>
               </seg>.<note xml:id="ftn7" type="footnote" n="7">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <seg style="">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
                     </seg>Presumably M's specimen that Baillon (1866), p. 321, indicates that he has seen.</p>
               </note> So you see, my dear Sir, my dread of one or the other portion of the collection being likely to be lost in these long sea-voyages proved but too well founded.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I have just read your admirable adress to the Linneans with great pleasure.<note xml:id="ftn8" type="footnote" n="8">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <seg style="">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
                     </seg>Bentham (1869), read 24 May 1869, published October 1869 (Gage &amp; Stearn (1868), p. 218). In his presidential address Bentham reviewed studies of the global geographic distribution of plants and of various groups of animals.</p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>As soon as I have done the <name key="Monocotyledoneae">Monocotyledoneae</name> I intend to publish a special volume of abridged diagnoses on Victorian plants &amp; let this volume be followed by a volume for each Austral Colony. At least the Victorian volume will have wood cuts, which to commence I have just made arrangements. The plan of these separate solitary volumes for each colony wil be so different to that of your work; that no clashing interests can arise.<note xml:id="ftn9" type="footnote" n="9">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>For issues concerning B79.06.04, the volume fitting this description, see Lucas, Maroske &amp; Brown-May (2006), pp. 36-44.</p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>It was with much regret, that I heard of your rheumatic sufferings, from which, I trust, you fully recovered.</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">Always with deep regard your</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Ferd von Mueller</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <name key="Salsolaceae">Salsolaceae</name> with all their desert-forms will have become a singular assemblage. I looked always well after them, when myself in the field, but sheep are apt to eat them down.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>A large box full of supplemental <name key="Monochlamydeae">Monochlamydeae</name> is all but ready.</p>
